\section{Model Assumptions and Setup}

\subsection{Assumptions Stated in the Lecture}

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item Events can be decomposed into mutually exclusive components.
    \item Conditional probabilities are well-defined for events with non-zero probability.
    \item Random variables are functions of experimental outcomes.
\end{itemize}

\vspace{0.5em}
\subsection{Conditions Under Which the Framework Applies}

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item Law of total probability applies when events form a partition of the sample space.
    \item Bayes’ theorem applies when conditional and prior probabilities are known.
    \item PMF applies only to discrete random variables.
\end{itemize}

\vspace{0.5em}
\subsection{Setup of Events or Variables}

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item Event decomposition:
    \[
        A = AB \cup AB^c
    \]
    \item Random variables map outcomes to numerical values.
    \item PMF defined over all possible values of a discrete random variable.
\end{itemize}

